# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mutual-tls
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mutual-tls/client-certificate] In cryptography, a **client certificate** is a type of digital certificate that is used by client systems to set up a secure connection to a remote server.
[src:mutual-tls/client-certificate] Certificates contain information about the client and are signed by a certificate authority.
[src:mutual-tls/client-certificate] Client certificates can provide mutual authentication without the use of passwords.
[src:mutual-tls/client-certificate] The Transport Layer Security protocol can optionally exchange and verify client certificates when setting up a connection.
[src:mutual-tls/client-certificate] This can consequently be used to authenticate to websites and wireless networks.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication is a desired characteristic in verification schemes that transmit sensitive data, in order to ensure data security.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication can be accomplished with two types of credentials: usernames and passwords, and public key certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication is often employed in the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Writing effective security schemes in IoT systems is challenging, especially when schemes are desired to be lightweight and have low computational costs.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication is a crucial security step that can defend against many adversarial attacks, which otherwise can have large consequences if IoT systems (such as e-Healthcare servers) are hacked.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] In scheme analyses done of past works, a lack of mutual authentication had been considered a weakness in data transmission schemes.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Schemes that have a mutual authentication step may use different methods of encryption, communication, and verification, but they all share one thing in common: each entity involved in the communication is verified.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] If Alice wants to communicate with Bob, they will both authenticate the other and verify that it is who they are expecting to communicate with before any data or messages are transmitted.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] The message is then decrypted with Bob's secret key, giving Alice's ID.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Bob sends Alice a message back, encrypted with Alice's public key, to show that Bob is a valid user.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] The message is then decrypted with Alice's secret key, giving Bob's ID.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] At this point, both parties are verified to be who they claim to be and safe for the other to communicate with.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Lastly, Alice and Bob will create a shared secret key so that they can continue communicating in a secure manner.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] To verify that mutual authentication has occurred successfully, Burrows-Abadi-Needham logic (BAN logic) is a well regarded and widely accepted method to use, because it verifies that a message came from a trustworthy entity.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] BAN logic first assumes an entity is not to be trusted, and then will verify its legality.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] or intercept a message, and sometimes alter the intended message for the recipient.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] The two parties openly receive messages without verifying the sender, so they do not realize an adversary has inserted themselves into the communication line.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication can prevent MITM attacks because both the sender and recipient verify each other before sending them their message keys, so if one of the parties is not verified to be who they claim they are, the session will end.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] A replay attack is similar to a MITM attack in which older messages are replayed out of context to fool the server.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] because timestamps are a verification factor that are used in the protocols.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] If the change in time is greater than the maximum allowed time delay, the session will be aborted.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Similarly, messages can include a randomly generated number to keep track of when a message was sent.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] before allowing any further communication and access.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Impersonation attacks refer to malicious attacks where a user or individual pretends to be an authorized user to gain unauthorized access to a system while feigning permission.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] When each party authenticates the other, they send each other a certificate that only the other party knows how to unscramble, verifying themselves as a trusted source.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] In this way, adversaries cannot use impersonation attacks because they do not have the correct certificate to act as if they are the other party.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication also ensures information integrity because if the parties are verified to be the correct source, then the information received is reliable as well.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] By default the TLS protocol only proves the identity of the server to the client using X.509 certificates, and the authentication of the client to the server is left to the application layer.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] TLS also offers client-to-server authentication using client-side X.509 authentication.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] As it requires provisioning of the certificates to the clients and involves a less user-friendly experience, it is rarely used in end-user applications.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] mTLS is also used in microservices-based applications based on runtimes such as Dapr, via systems like SPIFFE.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] While lightweight schemes and secure schemes are not mutually exclusive, adding a mutual authentication step to data transmissions protocols can often increase performance runtime and computational costs.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] This can become an issue for network systems that cannot handle large amounts of data or those that constantly have to update for new real-time data (e.g. location tracking, real-time health data).
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Thus, it becomes a desired characteristic of many mutual authentication schemes to have lightweight properties (e.g. have a low memory footprint) in order to accommodate the system that is storing a lot of data.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Many systems implement cloud computing, which allows quick access to large amounts of data, but sometimes large amounts of data can slow down communication.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Even with edge-based cloud computing, which is faster than general cloud computing due to a closer proximity between the server and user, lightweight schemes allow for more speed when managing larger amounts of data.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] One solution to keep schemes lightweight during the mutual authentication process is to limit the number of bits used during communication.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Applications that solely rely on device-to-device (D2D) communication, where multiple devices can communicate locally in close proximities, removes the third party network.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] This in turn can speed up communication time.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] However, the authentication still occurs through insecure channels, so researchers believe it is still important to ensure mutual authentication occurs in order to keep a secure scheme.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Schemes may sacrifice a better runtime or storage cost when ensuring mutual authentication in order to prioritize protecting the sensitive data.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] In mutual authentication schemes that require a user's input password as part of the verification process, there is a higher vulnerability to hackers because the password is human-made rather than a computer-generated certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] While applications could simply require users to use a computer-generated password, it is inconvenient for people to remember.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] User-made passwords and the ability to change one's password are important for making an application user-friendly, so many schemes work to accommodate the characteristic.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Researchers note that a password based protocol with mutual authentication is important because user identities and passwords are still protected, as the messages are only readable to the two parties involved.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] However, a negative aspect about password-based authentication is that password tables can take up a lot of memory space.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] One way around using a lot of memory during a password-based authentication scheme is to implement one-time passwords (OTP), which is a password sent to the user via SMS or email.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] OTPs are time-sensitive, which means that they will expire after a certain amount of time and that memory does not need to be stored.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Recently, more schemes have higher level authentication than password based schemes.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] While password-based authentication is considered as "single-factor authentication," schemes are beginning to implement smart card (two-factor) or biometric-based (three-factor) authentication schemes.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Smart cards are simpler to implement and easy for authentication, but still have risks of being tampered with.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Biometrics have grown more popular over password-based schemes because it is more difficult to copy or guess session keys when using biometrics, but it can be difficult to encrypt noisy data.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Due to these security risks and limitations, schemes can still employ mutual authentication regardless of how many authentication factors are added.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication is often found in schemes employed in the Internet of Things (IoT), where physical objects are incorporated into the Internet and can communicate via IP address.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Authentication schemes can be applied to many types of systems that involve data transmission.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] As the Internet's presence in mechanical systems increases, writing effective security schemes for large numbers of users, objects, and servers can become challenging, especially when needing schemes to be lightweight and have low computational costs.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Instead of password-based authentication, devices will use certificates to verify each other's identities.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication can be satisfied in radio network schemes, where data transmissions through radio frequencies are secure after verifying the sender and receiver.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Radio frequency identification (RFID) tags are commonly used for object detection, which many manufacturers are implementing into their warehouse systems for automation.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] This allows for a faster way to keep up with inventory and track objects.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] However, keeping track of items in a system with RFID tags that transmit data to a cloud server increases the chances of security risks, as there are now more digital elements to keep track of.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] A three way mutual authentication can occur between RFID tags, the tag readers, and the cloud network that stores this data in order to keep RFID tag data secure and unable to be manipulated.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Similarly, an alternate RFID tag and reader system that assigns designated readers to tags has been proposed for extra security and low memory cost.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Instead of considering all tag readers as one entity, only certain readers can read specific tags.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] With this method, if a reader is breached, it will not affect the whole system.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Individual readers will communicate with specific tags during mutual authentication, which runs in constant time as readers use the same private key for the authentication process.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Many e-Healthcare systems that remotely monitor patient health data use wireless body area networks (WBAN) that transmit data through radio frequencies.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] This is beneficial for patients that should not be disturbed while being monitored, and can reduced the workload for medical worker and allow them to focus on the more hands-on jobs.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] e-Healthcare clouds are another way to store patient data collected remotely.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Clouds are useful for storing large amounts of data, such as medical information, that can be accessed by many devices whenever needed.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Telecare Medical Information Systems (TMIS), an important way for medical patients to receive healthcare remotely, can ensure secured data with mutual authentication verification schemes.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Blockchain is one way that has been proposed to mutually authenticate the user to the database, by authenticating with the main mediBchain node and keeping patient anonymity.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Fog-cloud computing is a networking system that can handle large amounts of data, but still has limitations regarding computational and memory cost.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mobile edge computing (MEC) is considered to be an improved, more lightweight fog-cloud computing networking system, and can be used for medical technology that also revolves around location-based data.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Due to the large physical range required of locational tracking, 5G networks can send data to the edge of the cloud to store data.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] An application like smart watches that track patient health data can be used to call the nearest hospital if the patient shows a negative change in vitals.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Fog node networks can be implemented in car automation, keeping data about the car and its surrounding states secure.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] By authenticating the fog nodes and the vehicle, vehicular handoff becomes a safe process and the car’s system is safe from hackers.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Many systems that do not require a human user as part of the system also have protocols that mutually authenticate between parties.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] In unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) systems, a platform authentication occurs rather than user authentication.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication during vehicle communication prevents one vehicle's system from being breached, which can then affect the whole system negatively.
[src:mutual-tls/mutual-authentication] For example, a system of drones can be employed for agriculture work and cargo delivery, but if one drone were to be breached, the whole system has the potential to collapse.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In cryptography, a **public-key certificate**, also known as a **digital certificate** or **identity certificate**, is an electronic document used to prove the valid attribution of a public key to the identity of its holder.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The certificate includes the public key and information about it, information about the identity of its owner (called the subject), and the digital signature of an entity that has verified the certificate's contents (called the issuer).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] If the party examining the certificate trusts the issuer and finds the signature to be a valid signature of that issuer, then it can use the included public key to interact securely with the certificate's subject.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In email encryption, code signing, and e-signature systems, a certificate's subject is typically a person or organization.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] However, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) a certificate's subject is typically a computer or other device, though TLS certificates may identify organizations or individuals in addition to their core role in identifying devices.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] TLS, sometimes called by its older name Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), is notable for being a part of HTTPS, a protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In a typical public-key infrastructure (PKI) scheme, the certificate issuer is a certificate authority (CA), usually a company that charges customers a fee to issue certificates for them.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] By contrast, in a web of trust scheme, individuals sign each other's keys directly, in a format that performs a similar function to a public-key certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate is typically requested from a PKI using a CSR, which needs to be transferred using a secure certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The parties involved in the enrollment process must verify the authenticity, integrity, and authorization of the CSR, for which the certificate issuer bears the main responsibility.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In case of key compromise or other situations that may lead to unauthorized use, a certificate may need to be revoked.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The general format for public-key and attribute certificates is defined by X.509.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] For public-key certificates, the format has been profiled by the IETF for Internet-related use cases, such as Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A digital certificate system provides a chain of trust, meaning most certificates can be validated against parent certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The chain starts with a **root certificate**, which serves as a trust anchor (a.k.a. root of trust).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This certificate is self-signed (see below) and has no parent.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The issuing certificate authority uses other methods to safeguard and validate this certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] An **intermediate certificate** has a purpose similar to that of the root certificate – its only use is to sign other certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] However, an intermediate certificate is not self-signed.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A root certificate or another intermediate certificate needs to sign it.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] An **end-entity certificate**, or **leaf certificate**, is any certificate that cannot sign other certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] For instance, TLS/SSL server and client certificates, email certificates, code signing certificates, and qualified certificates are all end-entity certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol – as well as its outdated predecessor, the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) protocol – ensures that the communication between a client computer and a server is secure.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The protocol requires the server to present a digital certificate, proving that it is the intended destination.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A trusted certificate authority has signed the certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The *Subject* field of the certificate must identify the primary hostname of the server as the *Common Name*.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This means that the name listed in the certificate should exactly match the domain name users connect to (for example, `www.example.com`), ensuring that the certificate is valid for that specific hostname.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The hostname must be publicly accessible, not using private addresses or reserved domains.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be valid for multiple hostnames (e.g., a domain and its subdomains).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Such certificates are commonly called *Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates* or *Unified Communications Certificates (UCC)*.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] These certificates contain the Subject Alternative Name field, though many CAs also put them into the *Subject Common Name* field for backward compatibility.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] If some of the hostnames contain an asterisk (*), a certificate may also be called a wildcard certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Once the certification path validation is successful, the client can establish an encrypted connection with the server.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Internet-facing servers, such as public Web servers, must obtain their certificates from a trusted, public certificate authority (CA).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Client certificates authenticate the client connecting to a TLS service, for instance to provide access control.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Because most services provide access to individuals, rather than devices, most client certificates contain an email address or personal name rather than a hostname.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In addition, the certificate authority that issues the client certificate is usually the service provider to which client connects because it is the provider that needs to perform authentication.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] While most web browsers support client certificates, the most common form of authentication on the Internet is a username and password pair.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Client certificates are more common in virtual private networks (VPN) and Remote Desktop Services, where they authenticate devices.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In accordance with the S/MIME protocol, email certificates can both establish the message integrity and encrypt messages.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] To establish encrypted email communication, the communicating parties must have their digital certificates in advance.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Each must send the other one digitally signed email and opt to import the sender's certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Some publicly trusted certificate authorities provide email certificates, but more commonly S/MIME is used when communicating within a given organization, and that organization runs its own CA, which is trusted by participants in that email system.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A self-signed certificate is a certificate with a subject that matches its issuer, and a signature that can be verified by its own public key.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Although this type of certificate is worthless for establishing remote trust between unacquainted parties, it has full trust value when the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] As discussed above (in § Chain of trust), a root certificate is a self-signed certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The certificate authority, which is the sole user of the certificate, uses other means to validate and safeguard it.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Another example is the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows, which issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of the encrypting user, and uses it to transparently decrypt data on the fly.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates are an extension to X.509 that allows various values to be associated with a security certificate using a `subjectAltName` field.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] These values are called *Subject Alternative Names* (SANs).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] As of May 2000, Subject Alternative Names are the preferred method of adding DNS names to certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The previous method of putting DNS names in the `commonName` field is now deprecated.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Google Chrome version 58 (March 2017) removed support for checking the `commonName` field at all, instead only looking at the SANs.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] As shown in the picture of Wikimedia's section on the right, the SAN field can contain wildcards.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Not all vendors support or endorse mixing wildcards into SAN certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate which uses an asterisk `*` (the *wildcard*) in the domain name portion of it subject is called a Wildcard certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Through the use of `*`, a single certificate may be used for multiple sub-domains.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] It is commonly used for transport layer security in computer networking.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Instead of getting separate certificates for subdomains, you can use a single certificate for all main domains and subdomains and reduce cost.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Note possible exceptions by CAs, for example wildcard-plus cert by DigiCert contains an automatic "Plus" property for the naked domain `example.com`.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Only a single level of subdomain matching is supported.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] It is not possible to get a wildcard for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A workaround could be to add every virtual host name in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) extension, the major problem being that the certificate needs to be reissued whenever a new virtual server is added.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Wildcards can be added as domains in multi-domain certificates or Unified Communications Certificates (UCC).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In addition, wildcards themselves can have `subjectAltName` extensions, including other wildcards.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] For example, the wildcard certificate `*.wikipedia.org` has `*.m.wikimedia.org` as a Subject Alternative Name.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Thus it secures `www.wikipedia.org` as well as the completely different website name `meta.m.wikimedia.org`.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] RFC 6125 argues against wildcard certificates on security grounds, in particular "partial wildcards".
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The wildcard applies only to one level of the domain name.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] However, use of "partial-wildcard" certs is not recommended.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] As of 2011, partial wildcard support is optional, and is explicitly disallowed in SubjectAltName headers that are required for multi-name certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] All major browsers have deliberately **removed** support for partial-wildcard certificates; they will result in a "SSL_ERROR_BAD_CERT_DOMAIN" error.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Similarly, it is typical for standard libraries in programming languages to not support "partial-wildcard" certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] For example, any "partial-wildcard" certificate will not work with the latest versions of both Python and Go.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A cert with multiple wildcards in a name is not allowed.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A cert with `*` plus a top-level domain is not allowed.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] International domain names encoded in ASCII (A-label) are labels that are ASCII-encoded and begin with `xn--`.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] URLs with international labels cannot contain wildcards.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] These are some of the most common fields in certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Most certificates contain a number of fields not listed here.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Note that in terms of a certificate's X.509 representation, a certificate is not "flat" but contains these fields nested in various structures within the certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This is an example of a decoded SSL/TLS certificate retrieved from SSL.com's website.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The issuer's common name (CN) is shown as `SSL.com EV SSL Intermediate CA RSA R3`, identifying this as an Extended Validation (EV) certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Validated information about the website's owner (SSL Corp) is located in the `Subject` field.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Subject Alternative Name` field contains a list of domain names covered by the certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Extended Key Usage` and `X509v3 Key Usage` fields show all appropriate uses.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In the European Union, (advanced) electronic signatures on legal documents are commonly performed using digital signatures with accompanying identity certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] However, only qualified electronic signatures (which require using a qualified trust service provider and signature creation device) are given the same power as a physical signature.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In the X.509 trust model, a certificate authority (CA) is responsible for signing certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] These certificates act as an introduction between two parties, which means that a CA acts as a trusted third party.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A CA processes requests from people or organizations requesting certificates (called subscribers), verifies the information, and potentially signs an end-entity certificate based on that information.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] To perform this role effectively, a CA needs to have one or more broadly trusted root certificates or intermediate certificates and the corresponding private keys.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] CAs may achieve this broad trust by having their root certificates included in popular software, or by obtaining a cross-signature from another CA delegating trust.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Other CAs are trusted within a relatively small community, like a business, and are distributed by other mechanisms like Windows Group Policy.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Certificate authorities are also responsible for maintaining up-to-date revocation information about certificates they have issued, indicating whether certificates are still valid.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] They provide this information through Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and/or Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Some of the larger certificate authorities in the market include IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Some major software contain a list of certificate authorities that are trusted by default.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This makes it easier for end-users to validate certificates, and easier for people or organizations that request certificates to know which certificate authorities can issue a certificate that will be broadly trusted.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This is particularly important in HTTPS, where a web site operator generally wants to get a certificate that is trusted by nearly all potential visitors to their web site.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The policies and processes a provider uses to decide which certificate authorities their software should trust are called root programs.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Browsers other than Firefox generally use the operating system's facilities to decide which certificate authorities are trusted.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] So, for instance, Chrome on Windows trusts the certificate authorities included in the Microsoft Root Program, while on macOS or iOS, Chrome trusts the certificate authorities in the Apple Root Program.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Edge and Safari use their respective operating system trust stores as well, but each is only available on a single OS.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Firefox uses the Mozilla Root Program trust store on all platforms.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The Mozilla Root Program is operated publicly, and its certificate list is part of the open source Firefox web browser, so it is broadly used outside Firefox.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] For instance, while there is no common Linux Root Program, many Linux distributions, like Debian, include a package that periodically copies the contents of the Firefox trust list, which is then used by applications.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Root programs generally provide a set of valid purposes with the certificates they include.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] For instance, some CAs may be considered trusted for issuing TLS server certificates, but not for code signing certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This is indicated with a set of trust bits in a root certificate storage system.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The most common use of certificates is for HTTPS-based web sites.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A web browser validates that an HTTPS web server is authentic, so that the user can feel secure that his/her interaction with the web site has no eavesdroppers and that the web site is who it claims to be.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This security is important for electronic commerce.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In practice, a web site operator obtains a certificate by applying to a certificate authority with a certificate signing request.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The certificate request is an electronic document that contains the web site name, company information and the public key.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The certificate provider signs the request, thus producing a public certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] During web browsing, this public certificate is served to any web browser that connects to the web site and proves to the web browser that the provider believes it has issued a certificate to the owner of the web site.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Further, the relationship between the purchaser of the certificate, the operator of the web site, and the generator of the web site content may be tenuous and is not guaranteed.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] At best, the certificate guarantees uniqueness of the web site, provided that the web site itself has not been compromised (hacked) or the certificate issuing process subverted.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider can opt to issue three types of certificates, each requiring its own degree of vetting rigor.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In order of increasing rigor (and naturally, cost) they are: Domain Validation, Organization Validation and Extended Validation.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] These rigors are loosely agreed upon by voluntary participants in the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue a domain-validated (DV) certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can demonstrate one vetting criterion: the right to administratively manage the affected DNS domain(s).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue an organization validation (OV) class certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can meet two criteria: the right to administratively manage the domain name in question, and perhaps, the organization's actual existence as a legal entity.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider publishes its OV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] To acquire an Extended Validation (EV) certificate, the purchaser must persuade the certificate provider of its legal identity, including manual verification checks by a human.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] As with OV certificates, a certificate provider publishes its EV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Until 2019, major browsers such as Chrome and Firefox generally offered users a visual indication of the legal identity when a site presented an EV certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This was done by showing the legal name before the domain, and a bright green color to highlight the change.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Most browsers deprecated this feature providing no visual difference to the user on the type of certificate used.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This change followed security concerns raised by forensic experts and successful attempts to purchase EV certificates to impersonate famous organizations, proving the inefficiency of these visual indicators and highlighting potential abuses.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] A web browser will give no warning to the user if a web site suddenly presents a different certificate, even if that certificate has a lower number of key bits, even if it has a different provider, and even if the previous certificate had an expiry date far into the future.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Where certificate providers are under the jurisdiction of governments, those governments may have the freedom to order the provider to generate any certificate, such as for the purposes of law enforcement.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Subsidiary wholesale certificate providers also have the freedom to generate any certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] All web browsers come with an extensive built-in list of trusted root certificates, many of which are controlled by organizations that may be unfamiliar to the user.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] Each of these organizations is free to issue any certificate for any web site and have the guarantee that web browsers that include its root certificates will accept it as genuine.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In this instance, end users must rely on the developer of the browser software to manage its built-in list of certificates and on the certificate providers to behave correctly and to inform the browser developer of problematic certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] While uncommon, there have been incidents in which fraudulent certificates have been issued: in some cases, the browsers have detected the fraud; in others, some time passed before browser developers removed these certificates from their software.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] The list of built-in certificates is also not limited to those provided by the browser developer: users (and to a degree applications) are free to extend the list for special purposes such as for company intranets.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This means that if someone gains access to a machine and can install a new root certificate in the browser, that browser will recognize websites that use the inserted certificate as legitimate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] For provable security, this reliance on something external to the system has the consequence that any public-key certification scheme has to rely on some special setup assumption, such as the existence of a certificate authority.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] In spite of the limitations described above, certificate-authenticated TLS is considered mandatory by all security guidelines whenever a web site hosts confidential information or performs material transactions.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-certificate] This is because, in practice, in spite of the weaknesses described above, web sites secured by public-key certificates are still more secure than unsecured http:// web sites.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] A **public key infrastructure** (**PKI**) is a set of roles, policies, hardware, software and procedures used to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key cryptography set-ups.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] In cryptography, a PKI is an arrangement that *binds* public keys with respective identities of entities (like people and organizations).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The binding is established through a process of registration and issuance of certificates at and by a certificate authority (CA).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Depending on the assurance level of the binding, this may be carried out by an automated process or under human supervision.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] When done over a network, this requires using a secure certificate enrollment or certificate management protocol such as CMP.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI role that may be delegated by a CA to assure valid and correct registration is called a *registration authority* (RA).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] An RA is responsible for accepting requests for digital certificates and authenticating the entity making the request.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] RAs, however, do not sign or issue certificates (i.e., an RA is delegated certain tasks on behalf of a CA)." While Microsoft may have referred to a subordinate CA as an RA, this is incorrect according to the X.509 PKI standards.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] RAs do not have the signing authority of a CA and only manage the vetting and provisioning of certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] In the case of Microsoft Standalone CAs, the function of RA does not exist since all of the procedures controlling the CA are based on the administration and access procedure associated with the system hosting the CA and the CA itself rather than Active Directory.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Most non-Microsoft commercial PKI solutions offer a stand-alone RA component.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] An entity must be uniquely identifiable within each CA domain on the basis of information about that entity.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] A third-party validation authority (VA) can provide this entity information on behalf of the CA.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The X.509 standard defines the most commonly used format for public key certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] PKI provides "trust services" - in plain terms trusting the actions or outputs of entities, be they people or computers.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Trust service objectives respect one or more of the following capabilities: Confidentiality, Integrity and Authenticity (CIA).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Public-key cryptography is a cryptographic technique that enables entities to securely communicate on an insecure public network, and reliably verify the identity of an entity via digital signatures.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] A public key infrastructure (PKI) is a system for the creation, storage, and distribution of digital certificates, which are used to verify that a particular public key belongs to a certain entity.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI creates digital certificates that map public keys to entities, securely stores these certificates in a central repository and revokes them if needed.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The primary role of the CA is to digitally sign and publish the public key bound to a given user.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] This is done using the CA's own private key, so that trust in the user key relies on one's trust in the validity of the CA's key.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] When the CA is a third party separate from the user and the system, then it is called the Registration Authority (RA), which may or may not be separate from the CA.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The key-to-user binding is established, depending on the level of assurance the binding has, by software or under human supervision.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The term trusted third party (TTP) may also be used for certificate authority (CA).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Moreover, PKI is itself often used as a synonym for a CA implementation.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or mis-issued certificate until expiry.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] In this model of trust relationships, a CA is a trusted third party – trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The top spot has been held by Symantec (or VeriSign before it was purchased by Symantec) ever since [our] survey began, with it currently accounting for just under a third of all certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Following major issues in how certificate issuing was managed, all major players gradually distrusted Symantec-issued certificates, starting in 2017 and completed in 2021.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] This approach involves a server that acts as an offline certificate authority within a single sign-on system.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] A single sign-on server will issue digital certificates into the client system, but never stores them.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Users can execute programs, etc. with the temporary certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] It is common to find this solution variety with X.509-based certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Starting Sep 2020, TLS Certificate Validity reduced to 13 Months.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] An alternative approach to the problem of public authentication of public key information is the web-of-trust scheme, which uses self-signed certificates and third-party attestations of those certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The singular term "web of trust" does not imply the existence of a single web of trust, or common point of trust, but rather one of any number of potentially disjoint "webs of trust".
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Examples of implementations of this approach are PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) and GnuPG (an implementation of OpenPGP, the standardized specification of PGP).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Because PGP and implementations allow the use of e-mail digital signatures for self-publication of public key information, it is relatively easy to implement one's own web of trust.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] One of the benefits of the web of trust, such as in PGP, is that it can interoperate with a PKI CA fully trusted by all parties in a domain (such as an internal CA in a company) that is willing to guarantee certificates, as a trusted introducer.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] If the "web of trust" is completely trusted then, because of the nature of a web of trust, trusting one certificate is granting trust to all the certificates in that web.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI is only as valuable as the standards and practices that control the issuance of certificates and including PGP or a personally instituted web of trust could significantly degrade the trustworthiness of that enterprise's or domain's implementation of PKI.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Another alternative, which does not deal with public authentication of public key information, is the simple public key infrastructure (SPKI), which grew out of three independent efforts to overcome the complexities of X.509 and PGP's web of trust.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not associate users with persons, since the *key* is what is trusted, rather than the person.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not use any notion of trust, as the verifier is also the issuer.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] This is called an "authorization loop" in SPKI terminology, where authorization is integral to its design.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] This type of PKI is specially useful for making integrations of PKI that do not rely on third parties for certificate authorization, certificate information, etc.; a good example of this is an air-gapped network in an office.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Decentralized identifiers (DIDs) eliminate dependence on centralized registries for identifiers as well as centralized certificate authorities for key management, which is the standard in hierarchical PKI.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] In cases where the DID registry is a distributed ledger, each entity can serve as its own root authority.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] This architecture is referred to as decentralized PKI (DPKI).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Developments in PKI occurred in the early 1970s at the British intelligence agency GCHQ, where James Ellis, Clifford Cocks and others made important discoveries related to encryption algorithms and key distribution.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Because developments at GCHQ are highly classified, the results of this work were kept secret and not publicly acknowledged until the mid-1990s.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The public disclosure of both secure key exchange and asymmetric key algorithms in 1976 by Diffie, Hellman, Rivest, Shamir, and Adleman changed secure communications entirely.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Assorted cryptographic protocols were invented and analyzed within which the new cryptographic primitives could be effectively used.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] With the invention of the World Wide Web and its rapid spread, the need for authentication and secure communication became still more acute.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Commercial reasons alone (e.g., e-commerce, online access to proprietary databases from web browsers) were sufficient.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Taher Elgamal and others at Netscape developed the SSL protocol ('https' in Web URLs); it included key establishment, server authentication (prior to v3, one-way only), and so on.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI structure was thus created for Web users/sites wishing secure communications.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Vendors and entrepreneurs saw the possibility of a large market, started companies (or new projects at existing companies), and began to agitate for legal recognition and protection from liability.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Consumer groups raised questions about privacy, access, and liability considerations, which were more taken into consideration in some jurisdictions than in others.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The enacted laws and regulations differed, and there were technical and operational problems in converting PKI schemes into successful commercial operation.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Progress has been much slower than pioneers had imagined it would be.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] By the first few years of the 21st century, the underlying cryptographic engineering was clearly not easy to deploy correctly.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Operating procedures (manual or automatic) were not easy to correctly design (nor even if so designed, to execute perfectly, which the engineering required).
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] The standards that existed were insufficient.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] PKI vendors have found a market, but it is not quite the market envisioned in the mid-1990s, and it has grown both more slowly and in somewhat different ways than were anticipated.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] PKIs have not solved some of the problems they were expected to, and several major vendors have gone out of business or been acquired by others.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] PKI has had the most success in government implementations; the largest PKI implementation to date is the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) PKI infrastructure for the Common Access Cards program.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Some argue that purchasing certificates for securing websites by SSL/TLS and securing software by code signing is a costly venture for small businesses.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] However, the emergence of free alternatives, such as Let's Encrypt, has changed this.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] HTTP/2, the latest version of HTTP protocol, allows unsecured connections in theory; in practice, major browser companies have made it clear that they would support this protocol only over a PKI secured TLS connection.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Web browser implementation of HTTP/2 including Chrome, Firefox, Opera, and Edge supports HTTP/2 only over TLS by using the ALPN extension of the TLS protocol.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] This would mean that, to get the speed benefits of HTTP/2, website owners would be forced to purchase SSL/TLS certificates controlled by corporations.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Currently the majority of web browsers are shipped with pre-installed intermediate certificates issued and signed by a certificate authority, by public keys certified by so-called root certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] This means browsers need to carry a large number of different certificate providers, increasing the risk of a key compromise.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] When a key is known to be compromised, it could be fixed by revoking the certificate, but such a compromise is not easily detectable and can be a huge security breach.
[src:mutual-tls/public-key-infrastructure] Browsers have to issue a security patch to revoke intermediary certificates issued by a compromised root certificate authority.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:mutual-tls/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In cryptography, **X.509** is an International Telecommunication Union (ITU) standard defining the format of public key certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] X.509 certificates are used in many Internet protocols, including TLS/SSL, which is the basis for HTTPS, the secure protocol for browsing the web.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] They are also used in offline applications, like electronic signatures.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] An X.509 certificate binds an identity to a public key using a digital signature.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] A certificate contains an identity (a hostname, or an organization, or an individual) and a public key (RSA, DSA, ECDSA, ed25519, etc.), and is either signed by a certificate authority (CA) or is self-signed.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] When a certificate is signed by a trusted certificate authority, or validated by other means, someone holding that certificate can use the public key it contains to establish secure communications with another party, or validate documents digitally signed by the corresponding private key.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] X.509 is defined by the ITU's "Standardization Sector" (ITU-T's SG17), in ITU-T Study Group 17 and is based on Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1), another ITU-T standard.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] X.509 was initially issued on July 3, 1988, and was begun in association with the X.500 standard.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The first tasks of it was providing users with secure access to information resources and avoiding a cryptographic man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] It assumes a strict hierarchical system of certificate authorities (CAs) for issuing the certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] This contrasts with web of trust models, like PGP, where anyone (not just special CAs) may sign and thus attest to the validity of others' key certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Version 3 of X.509 includes the flexibility to support other topologies like bridges and meshes.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] It can be used in a peer-to-peer, OpenPGP-like web of trust, but was rarely used that way as of 2004.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The X.500 system has only been implemented by sovereign nations for state identity information sharing treaty fulfillment purposes, and the IETF's Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509) (PKIX) working group has adapted the standard to the more flexible organization of the Internet.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In fact, the term *X.509 certificate* usually refers to the IETF's PKIX certificate and CRL profile of the X.509 v3 certificate standard, as specified in RFC 5280, commonly called PKIX for *Public Key Infrastructure (X.509)*.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] An early issue with Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) and X.509 certificates was the well known "which directory" problem.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The problem is the client does not know where to fetch missing intermediate certificates because the global X.500 directory never materialized.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The problem was mitigated by including all intermediate certificates in a request.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] For example, early web servers only sent the web server's certificate to the client.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Clients that lacked an intermediate CA certificate or where to find them failed to build a valid path from the CA to the server's certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] To work around the problem, web servers now send all the intermediate certificates along with the web server's certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] While PKIX refers to the IETF's or Internet's PKI standard, there are many other PKIs with different policies.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] For example, the US Government has its own PKI with its own policies, and the CA/Browser Forum has its own PKI with its own policies.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The US Government's PKI is a massive book of over 2500 pages.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] If an organization's PKI diverges too much from that of the IETF or CA/Browser Forum, then the organization risks losing interoperability with common tools like web browsers, cURL, and Wget.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] For example, if a PKI has a policy of only issuing certificates on Monday, then common tools like cURL and Wget will not enforce the policy and allow a certificate issued on a Tuesday.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] X.509 certificates bind an identity to a public key using a digital signature.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In the X.509 system, there are two types of certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The second is an end-entity certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] A CA certificate can issue other certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The top level, self-signed CA certificate is sometimes called the Root CA certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Other CA certificates are called intermediate CA or subordinate CA certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] An end-entity certificate identifies the user, like a person, organization or business.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] An end-entity certificate *cannot* issue other certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] An end-entity certificate is sometimes called a leaf certificate since no other certificates can be issued below it.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] An organization that wants a signed certificate requests one from a CA using a protocol like Certificate Signing Request (CSR), Simple Certificate Enrollment Protocol (SCEP) or Certificate Management Protocol (CMP).
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The organization first generates a key pair, keeping the private key secret and using it to sign the CSR.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The CSR contains information identifying the applicant and the applicant's public key that is used to verify the signature of the CSR - and the Distinguished Name (DN) that is unique for the person, organization or business.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The CSR may be accompanied by other credentials or proofs of identity required by the certificate authority.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The CSR will be validated using a Registration Authority (RA), and then the certification authority will issue a certificate binding a public key to a particular distinguished name.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The roles registration authority and certification authority are usually separate business units under separation of duties to reduce the risk of fraud.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] An organization's trusted root certificates can be distributed to all employees so that they can use the company PKI system.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] For example, Firefox provides a CSV and/or HTML file containing a list of Included CAs.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] X.509 and RFC 5280 also include standards for certificate revocation list (CRL) implementations.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Another IETF-approved way of checking a certificate's validity is the Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP).
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Firefox 3.0 enabled OCSP checking by default, as did versions of Windows from at least Vista and later.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The structure foreseen by the standards is expressed in a formal language, Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1).
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The Extensions field, if present, is a sequence of one or more certificate extensions.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Each extension has its own unique ID, expressed as object identifier (OID), which is a set of values, together with either a critical or non-critical indication.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] A certificate-using system must reject the certificate if it encounters a critical extension that it does not recognize, or a critical extension that contains information that it cannot process.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] A non-critical extension may be ignored if it is not recognized, but must be processed if it is recognized.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The structure of version 1 is given in RFC 1422.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The inner format of issuer and subject unique identifiers specified in *X.520 The Directory: Selected attribute types* recommendation.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] ITU-T introduced issuer and subject unique identifiers in version 2 to permit the reuse of issuer or subject name after some time.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] An example of reuse will be when a CA goes bankrupt and its name is deleted from the country's public list.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] After some time another CA with the same name may register itself, even though it is unrelated to the first one.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] However, IETF recommends that no issuer and subject names be reused.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Therefore, version 2 is not widely deployed in the Internet.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Extensions were introduced in version 3.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] A CA can use extensions to issue a certificate only for a specific purpose (e.g. only for signing digital objects).
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In all versions, the serial number must be unique for each certificate issued by a specific CA (as mentioned in RFC 5280).
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] RFC 5280 (and its predecessors) defines a number of certificate extensions which indicate how the certificate should be used.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Most of them are arcs from the `joint-iso-ccitt(2) ds(5) id-ce(29)` OID.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In general when using RFC 5280, if a certificate has several extensions restricting its use, all restrictions must be satisfied for a given use to be appropriate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The RFC gives the specific example of a certificate containing both keyUsage and extendedKeyUsage: in this case, both must be processed and the certificate can only be used if both extensions are coherent in specifying the usage of a certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] For example, NSS uses both extensions to specify certificate usage.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Certification authorities operating under the CA/Browser Forum's PKI issue certificates with varying levels of validation.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The different validations provide different levels of assurances that a certificate represents what it is supposed to.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] For example, a web server can be validated at the lowest level of assurances using an email called *Domain Validation (DV)*.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Or a web server can be validated at a higher level of assurances using more detailed methods called *Extended Validation (EV)*.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In practice, a DV certificate means a certificate was issued for a domain like `example.com` after control over that domain was asserted, e.g. by responding to an email sent to `webmaster@example.com`.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] An EV certificate means a certificate was issued for a domain like `example.com`, and a company like Example, LLC is the owner of the domain, and the owner was verified by Articles of Incorporation.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Extended validation does not add any additional security controls, so the secure channel setup using an EV certificate is not "stronger" than a channel setup using a different level of validation like DV.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Extended validation is signaled in a certificate using X.509 v3 extension.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Each CA uses a different Object Identifier (OID) to assert extended validation.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] There is no single OID to indicate extended validation, which complicates user agent programming.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Each user agent must have a list of OIDs that indicate extended validation.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The CA/Browser Forum's PKI recognizes extended validation.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Other PKIs, like the Internet's PKI (PKIX), do not place any special emphasis on extended validation.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Tools using PKIX policies, like cURL and Wget, simply treat an EV certificate like any other certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Until 2019, many browsers used to provide strong visual feedback in the URL bar to the user to indicate a site provides an EV certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Following studies and reports that showed the ineffectiveness of EV certificates and their utility to criminals for injecting misleading elements into the central part of the browser's UI, all major browsers removed their previous prominent visual feedback from the URL bar.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Instead, since 2019, browsers such as Chromium and Firefox hide the EV issued-to information in sub-menus, where it is displayed in a neutral way, without any highlighting or mentioning of extended validation.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Security expert Peter Gutmann states CA's created EV certificates to restore profit levels after the Race to the Bottom cut into profits.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] During the race to the bottom CA's cut prices to lure consumers to purchase their certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] As a result, profits were reduced and CA's dropped the level of validation they were performing to the point there were nearly no assurances on a certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] There are several commonly used filename extensions for X.509 certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Some of these extensions are also used for other data such as private keys.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] PKCS#7 is a standard for signing or encrypting (officially called "enveloping") data.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Since the certificate is needed to verify signed data, it is possible to include them in the SignedData structure.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Each certificate (except the last one) is signed by the secret key corresponding to the next certificate in the chain (i.e. the signature of one certificate can be verified using the public key contained in the following certificate).
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The last certificate in the list is a trust anchor: a certificate that you trust because it was delivered to you by some trustworthy procedure.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Certificate chains are used in order to check that the public key (PK) contained in a target certificate (the first certificate in the chain) and other data contained in it effectively belongs to its subject.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In order to ascertain this, the signature on the target certificate is verified by using the PK contained in the following certificate, whose signature is verified using the next certificate, and so on until the last certificate in the chain is reached.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] As the last certificate is a trust anchor, successfully reaching it will prove that the target certificate can be trusted.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The description in the preceding paragraph is a simplified view on the certification path validation process, which involves additional checks, such as verifying validity dates on certificates, looking up CRLs, etc.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] A concrete certificate can be part of very different certificate chains (all of them valid).
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] This is because several CA certificates can be generated for the same subject and public key, but be signed with different private keys (from different CAs or different private keys from the same CA).
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] So, although a single X.509 certificate can have only one issuer and one CA signature, it can be validly linked to more than one certificate, building completely different certificate chains.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] This is crucial for cross-certification between PKIs and other applications.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In order to manage that user certificates existing in PKI 2 (like "User 2") are trusted by PKI 1, CA1 generates a certificate (cert2.1) containing the public key of CA2.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Now both "cert2 and cert2.1 (in green) have the same subject and public key, so there are two valid chains for cert2.2 (User 2): "cert2.2 → cert2" and "cert2.2 → cert2.1 → cert1".
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Similarly, CA2 can generate a certificate (cert1.1) containing the public key of CA1 so that user certificates existing in PKI 1 (like "User 1") are trusted by PKI 2.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Since both cert1 and cert3 contain the same public key (the old one), there are two valid certificate chains for cert5: "cert5 → cert1" and "cert5 → cert3 → cert2", and analogously for cert6.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] This allows that old user certificates (such as cert5) and new certificates (such as cert6) can be trusted indifferently by a party having either the new root CA certificate or the old one as trust anchor during the transition to the new CA keys.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] This is an example of a decoded X.509 certificate that was used in the past by wikipedia.org and several other Wikipedia websites.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] It was issued by GlobalSign, as stated in the Issuer field.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Its Subject field describes Wikipedia as an organization, and its Subject Alternative Name (SAN) field for DNS describes the hostnames for which it could be used.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The Subject Public Key Info field contains an ECDSA public key, while the signature at the bottom was generated by GlobalSign's RSA private key.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In a TLS connection, a properly-configured server would provide the intermediate as part of the handshake.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] However, it's also possible to retrieve the intermediate certificate by fetching the "CA Issuers" URL from the end-entity certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] This is an example of an intermediate certificate belonging to a certificate authority.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] This certificate signed the end-entity certificate above, and was signed by the root certificate below.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Note that the subject field of this intermediate certificate matches the issuer field of the end-entity certificate that it signed.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Also, the "subject key identifier" field in the intermediate matches the "authority key identifier" field in the end-entity certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] This is an example of a self-signed root certificate representing a certificate authority.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Its issuer and subject fields are the same, and its signature can be validated with its own public key.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Validation of the trust chain has to end here.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] If the validating program has this root certificate in its trust store, the end-entity certificate can be considered trusted for use in a TLS connection.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Otherwise, the end-entity certificate is considered untrusted.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] There are a number of publications about PKI problems by Bruce Schneier, Peter Gutmann and other security experts.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Implementations suffer from design flaws, bugs, different interpretations of standards and lack of interoperability of different standards.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Digital signature systems depend on secure cryptographic hash functions to work.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] When a public key infrastructure allows the use of a hash function that is no longer secure, an attacker can exploit weaknesses in the hash function to forge certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Specifically, if an attacker is able to produce a hash collision, they can convince a CA to sign a certificate with innocuous contents, where the hash of those contents is identical to the hash of another, malicious set of certificate contents, created by the attacker with values of their choosing.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The attacker can then append the CA-provided signature to their malicious certificate contents, resulting in a malicious certificate that appears to be signed by the CA.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Because the malicious certificate contents are chosen solely by the attacker, they can have different validity dates or hostnames than the innocuous certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The malicious certificate can even contain a "CA: true" field making it able to issue further trusted certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Exploiting a hash collision to forge X.509 signatures requires that the attacker be able to predict the data that the certificate authority will sign.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] This can be somewhat mitigated by the CA generating a random component in the certificates it signs, typically the serial number.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The CA/Browser Forum has required serial number entropy in its Baseline Requirements Section 7.1 since 2011.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] As of January 1, 2016, the Baseline Requirements forbid issuance of certificates using SHA-1.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] As of early 2017, Chrome and Firefox reject certificates that use SHA-1.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] As of May 2017 both Edge and Safari are also rejecting SHA-1 certificate.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] OpenSSL began rejecting SHA-1 certificates by default in version 3.0, released September 2021.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In 1995, the Internet Engineering Task Force in conjunction with the National Institute of Standards and Technology formed the Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509) working group.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The working group, concluded in June 2014, is commonly referred to as "PKIX." It produced RFCs and other standards documentation on using and deploying X.509 in practice.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] In particular it produced RFC 3280 and its successor RFC 5280, which define how to use X.509 in Internet protocols.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] TLS/SSL and HTTPS use the RFC 5280 profile of X.509, as do S/MIME (Secure Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions) and the EAP-TLS method for WiFi authentication.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Any protocol that uses TLS, such as SMTP, POP, IMAP, LDAP, XMPP, and many more, inherently uses X.509.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] IPsec can use the RFC 4945 profile for authenticating peers.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The OpenCable security specification defines its own profile of X.509 for use in the cable industry.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Devices like smart cards and TPMs often carry certificates to identify themselves or their owners.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The WS-Security standard defines authentication either through TLS or through its own certificate profile.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The Microsoft Authenticode code signing system uses X.509 to identify authors of computer programs.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] Secure Boot feature of UEFI uses X.509 to authenticate UEFI drivers or bootloaders during booting and disallow blocklisted drivers or bootloaders (by using Forbidden Key Exchange or dbx database).
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] The OPC UA industrial automation communication standard uses X.509.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] SSH generally uses a Trust On First Use security model and doesn't have need for certificates.
[src:mutual-tls/x-509] However, the popular OpenSSH implementation does support a CA-signed identity model based on its own non-X.509 certificate format.
